Yes. Here’s a buildable design for it.

Call it GeoAtlas for now:

a geospatial reasoning engine that predicts where a business will perform best by combining geometry, flows, economics, and semantics

At the data layer, this is very feasible now because open foundational map data exists through Overture’s place/building/transportation themes, OSM can be queried through Overpass, and H3 gives you a standard hierarchical spatial index for joining everything into one grid.  ￼

1) What the product does

A user asks:
	•	“Where should I open a gym?”
	•	“What’s the best second location for this café?”
	•	“Which trade areas are under-served for pediatric dentistry?”
	•	“Which corners look busy but are actually bad bets?”

The engine returns:
	•	ranked candidate sites
	•	predicted revenue band
	•	traffic and accessibility profile
	•	neighborhood fit score
	•	cannibalization risk
	•	confidence and top failure modes

The differentiator is not map display. It is decision support.

2) Core product surfaces

There are three surfaces.

Explorer
A map with layered scores: demand, accessibility, competition, rent pressure, demographic fit, semantic vibe.

Simulator
“What happens if I place this concept here?”
It estimates likely performance under assumptions.

Matcher
“Find me more places like my top-performing location.”
It does analog search over the city or country.

3) System architecture

A. World ingestion layer

Ingest and normalize:
	•	base map, roads, buildings, addresses
	•	places / POIs
	•	zoning / parcel / boundary data
	•	mobility and traffic proxies
	•	business listings and reviews
	•	commercial real estate listings
	•	census and household data
	•	optional card spend / foot traffic partners

Overture is a strong open foundation because it publishes normalized GeoParquet releases and currently includes six map-data themes; its Places guide says the places theme contains more than 64 million place features.  ￼

B. Spatial indexing layer

Everything gets indexed into H3 cells at multiple resolutions:
	•	coarse cells for citywide search
	•	medium cells for neighborhood analysis
	•	fine cells for site scoring

H3 is hierarchical and lets you aggregate and join disparate datasets by cell, which is exactly what you want for a model like this.  ￼

C. Entity graph layer

Represent the city as a graph:
	•	nodes: buildings, POIs, intersections, transit stops, parcels
	•	edges: roads, walk paths, transit links, visibility corridors
	•	hyperedges: trade areas, neighborhoods, catchments

This is where you store relationships like:
“this daycare is near dense young-family housing but poorly visible from arterial traffic.”

D. Feature store

For each candidate site or H3 cell, compute feature families:

Geometry
	•	lot size
	•	building area
	•	frontage
	•	parking estimate
	•	visibility / corner status
	•	nearby building density

Access
	•	walk-time to transit
	•	drive-time catchment
	•	traffic class
	•	ingress / egress friction
	•	daytime population reach

Competitive landscape
	•	nearby same-category count
	•	complementary-business density
	•	white-space score
	•	chain saturation
	•	anchor-neighbor effects

Economic
	•	rent proxy
	•	income / spend proxy
	•	employment density
	•	housing growth
	•	price sensitivity

Temporal
	•	seasonality
	•	year-over-year openings/closures
	•	construction / roadwork shocks
	•	neighborhood drift

Semantic
	•	review embeddings
	•	neighborhood “vibe” embeddings
	•	category fit
	•	brand-language similarity
	•	qualitative tags like family-heavy / commuter / nightlife / luxury

E. Model stack

Use four model families together.

1. Retrieval model
Find comparable sites and comparable businesses.

2. Prediction model
Estimate success metrics:
	•	revenue band
	•	survival probability
	•	time to breakeven
	•	footfall potential

Gradient-boosted trees or tabular deep models are good first choices here.

3. Graph model
Model spillovers and neighbor effects:
	•	anchors helping nearby stores
	•	cannibalization between same-brand sites
	•	cluster effects

4. LLM reasoning layer
Turns raw outputs into useful answers:
	•	explains why a location scored high
	•	compares tradeoffs
	•	answers natural-language queries
	•	extracts structured attributes from reviews, listings, permits, broker notes

The LLM should not be the source of truth. It should sit on top of the structured model.

4) Data model

Use four canonical objects.

Place
A business or landmark.

Site
A specific leasable candidate location.

Cell
An H3 region holding aggregated local signals.

Market graph
The network connecting sites, cells, and flows.

Suggested IDs:
	•	site_id
	•	brand_id
	•	h3_r8, h3_r10, h3_r12
	•	market_id
	•	trade_area_id

5) How scoring works

Each site gets a scorecard.

Opportunity Score =
demand fit
	•	access fit
	•	complementarity
	•	growth momentum
− competition pressure
− occupancy cost pressure
− operational friction

Then add a separate:

Confidence Score =
data coverage
	•	comp similarity quality
	•	signal agreement
− volatility
− missingness

Do not collapse everything into one number too early. Show sub-scores.

6) The semantic layer

This is where it becomes more than GIS.

You embed:
	•	reviews
	•	neighborhood descriptions
	•	listings
	•	menus / service descriptions
	•	local social text
	•	zoning notes / broker remarks

Then the system can answer:
	•	“Find neighborhoods with the feel of my best location, but cheaper.”
	•	“Show me high-income zones where customers talk more about convenience than ambiance.”
	•	“Where do boutique fitness signals appear before boutique fitness supply?”

Overture’s places taxonomy is useful here because the schema is actively maintained and its places categories are shifting toward basic_category and taxonomy, which is better for a long-lived category system.  ￼

7) MVP

Build the first version around one category in one metro.

Best MVP targets:
	•	coffee
	•	quick-service restaurants
	•	boutique fitness
	•	dental / medspa
	•	car wash
	•	daycare

For MVP, use:
	•	Overture + OSM for base places/buildings/roads
	•	one commercial listing feed or manual site imports
	•	census / ACS
	•	public transit GTFS if available
	•	review text from legally usable sources
	•	your own scoring model

Mapbox is a practical frontend/API layer for search, map rendering, and boundary/movement add-ons if you want a commercial stack; its current products include search APIs, and Mapbox says it also offers boundaries, traffic, and movement data products.  ￼

8) User workflow

A founder uploads:
	•	current store locations
	•	unit economics
	•	target customer
	•	minimum parking / frontage / square footage needs

The system then:
	1.	learns what “good” looks like from their winners and losers
	2.	searches the metro for analog sites
	3.	filters by hard constraints
	4.	simulates performance
	5.	returns top 20 candidates with reasons

That gets you to paid value fast.

9) The moat

The moat is not just “having map data.”

It is:
	•	cleaned entity resolution
	•	site outcome history
	•	feature engineering
	•	category-specific models
	•	feedback loop from real openings and closures
	•	operator trust

Overture and OSM reduce the barrier to entry on the raw map side, which means the moat shifts upward into modeling, proprietary outcomes, and workflow integration.  ￼

10) Failure modes

The biggest ones:

Bad ground truth
If you do not know which locations actually succeeded or failed, your model becomes decorative.

Selection bias
Chains choose sites differently than independents.

Semantic overreach
“Vibe” is useful, but it cannot replace rent, access, and catchment math.

Stale data
Road changes, tenant turnover, and construction can invalidate a site quickly.

Attribution errors
A great location can still fail because of bad operations.

So the product should always distinguish:
	•	site quality
	•	operator fit
	•	execution risk

11) Pantheon-native framing

In your language:
	•	terrain = city graph
	•	current = traffic, spend, attention
	•	anchors = transit, schools, employers, destinations
	•	harmonics = complementary business clusters
	•	dominance through coordination = placing the right nodes into the right field at the right time

That is the true wedge:
not brute competition, but superior placement intelligence.

12) Concrete stack

A practical v1 stack:
	•	storage: Postgres/PostGIS + object store
	•	spatial index: H3
	•	pipelines: Python + DuckDB + dbt
	•	vector store: pgvector or equivalent
	•	models: XGBoost/LightGBM + graph features
	•	orchestration: Airflow/Prefect
	•	API: FastAPI
	•	frontend: React + Mapbox GL JS
	•	batch inference: daily
	•	user-facing copilot: LLM with tool access to ranked site data

13) Ship order

Phase 1:
single metro, one vertical, ranked-site reports

Phase 2:
self-serve map explorer and what-if simulator

Phase 3:
portfolio optimization across multiple locations

Phase 4:
city-scale market prediction and developer/investor tools

14) The shortest sharp version

GeoAtlas = H3-indexed city graph + POI/building data + business outcome model + semantic neighborhood layer + LLM explainer

That is the machine.

And yes—this is exactly domination through coordination:
you do not fight over the map;
you learn to read the field better than everyone else.

